Sent: Tuesday, June 02, 1998 10:09 PM

[The following is some clinical information about three fatal cases who
visited the Infectious Disease Center of Osaka City General Hospital after
showing symptoms of hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD). This information
was [provided by Dr. Shiomi, who is a pediatrician at the Hospital, and
[who sends clinical specimens to our laboratory.
Case 1: Nine-month-old girl. She showed HFMD symptoms from July 11, 1997.
Her elder brother and sister also contracted HFMD. In the afternoon of July
14, she suddenly weakened and showed dyspnea, which urged her to visit the
Hospital. Six hours after the admission she died. Although lung edema was
observed by X-ray examination, no heart enlargement was seen.
Case 2: Fifteen-month-old boy. Although he contracted HFMD on August 17,
1997, his general condition was good at that time. In the morning of August
21, he became weak and visited the private clinic near his house. But, in
front of the door of the clinic, he vomited and his heart stopped suddenly.
He was sent to the Hospital to try to revive, but he died 4 hours after the
visit.
Case 3: Five-month-old boy. He had fever from September 25, 1997. In the
morning of September 28, he showed tachypnea and tachycardia, and was sent
to a emergency clinic where he was given artificial respiration.
Thereafter, he visited the Hospital. However, he died 12 hours after
admission. During the admission multi-organ dysfunction, such as
abnormalities of liver function and DIC, were observed. However, these
symptoms seemed to be secondary effects.
An EV-71 strain was isolated from a stool specimen of Case 3. Dr. Shiomi
commented that the clinical pictures of the fatal cases were very similar
to those reported from [Malaysia which suggested bulbar form paralysis and
lung edema were causes of death.
--
Y. Okuno
Head of the Department of Virology,
Osaka Prefectural Institute of Public Health
3-69, Nakamichi 1-chome, Higashinari-ku,
Osaka 537-0025, Japan
